observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
i) comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-001 specifically on the submission of approved DTRs as basis for the payroll before drawing cash advance and submission of verified ARs in the liquidation thereof;
ii) refrain from incurring advance payment by preparing the payroll after the end of the pay period and base the same on the approved DTRs submitted;
iii) include in the JO contracts the duties and functions of the JO personnel; and
iv) ensure the correctness and completeness of details in the DTRs of JO and COS personnel.

We recommended and (a) Local Chief Executive agreed to (i) direct the Inventory Team to conduct physical count and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) and submit a copy thereof to the Audit Team; 

(ii) require the Accounting and Treasury Offices to prepare and update PPE ledger cards for each PPE sub-account so that general ledger balances of PPE are supported by independent and reliable records; 

(iii) instruct the Accounting Office to exert best effort to secure the necessary documents and reports so that appropriate depreciation can be provided; 

(b) Management execute valid donation documents for accounting recognition purposes; and 

(c) Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant recover the records that would determine the carrying value of the demolished structures and thereafter derecognize them in the books of the Municipality.

We recommended and Local Chief Executive agreed to:

a)	direct the MDRRMO to (i) review the DRRM projects and activities that were not implemented in CY 2019 and program their execution, if still warranted by the present circumstances, so that calamity-issues sought to be addressed by the initiatives are given the necessary solutions; 

(ii) plan carefully the programs, projects and activities to ensure that these are implemented on the set timeline; 

(iii) procure the tools and equipment prescribed in the Disaster Preparedness Manual which are not yet available in the agency; 

(iv) always prepare a comprehensive and inclusive LDRRMFIP particularly disclosing the list of initiatives charged against the unexpended calamity fund transferred to special trust account; and

b)	require the concerned offices to submit the lacking documents.

We recommended and Management agreed that the:

a.	Management, moving forward, furnish the Auditor advance copies of contracts of similar transactions and their supporting documents within five (5) days from the execution thereof;

b.	Local Chief Executive direct the Bids and Awards Committee to strictly adhere to the above-cited provisions of R.A. No. 9184 and its RIRR in the procurement activities; 

c.	Municipal Accountant review thoroughly all claims presented for payment prior to approval to ensure that only properly and completely documented transactions/disbursements shall be paid;

d.	Concerned agency officials, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer, clearly state in the contract the project duration for transparency purposes; and

e.	Concerned agency officials and personnel submit immediately the lacking documents to the Audit Team.

We recommended and Management agreed that the:

a.	Management (i) continue the practice of ensuring optimal use of development funds so that socio-economic projects that are beneficial to the agency’s constituents are timely implemented; and 

(ii) give priority on the implementation of PPAs from its continuing appropriation so that expected outputs and outcomes will be realized in the coming fiscal year;

b.	Local Chief Executive direct the Bids and Awards Committee and its Secretariat, Accounting Office and the Engineering Office to submit the lacking documents;

c.	Concerned agency officials, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer, clearly state in the contract the project duration for transparency purposes; and

d.	Management strictly adhere to the provisions of R.A. No. 9184 and its RIRR particularly, the acceptance of a project which should be one year after its completion.

We recommended and Local Chief Executive agreed to direct (a) all concerned personnel to expedite the preparation and submission of documents pertaining to their transactions so as not to cause delays; 

(b) the Municipal Accountant to prepare the interim financial statements and submit them quarterly; and 

(c) strict compliance with the regulation on the rendition of accounts and submission of financial reports in order not to delay the verification and post-audit activities.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to require the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board to (i) include pre-identified solid wastes interventions in the annual budget of the agency to ensure funding for their implementation; 

(ii) monitor the implementation and completion of said interventions with the end in view of assuring that desired outputs and outcomes are fully achieved; 

(iii) devote time to convene regularly so that problems, issues, best practices, and success stories relating to the agency’s solid waste management campaign are discussed; 

(iv) revisit the provisions embodied in the Municipal Ordinance on the Comprehensive Solid Waste Management and identify mechanics to mobilize the same; and 

(v) fully comply with its mandated functions as enumerated in R.A. No. 9003 and its IRR.

We recommended and Management agreed that the GFPS Focal Person (i) submit in writing the changes in the DILG-approved GAD Plan and Budget (GPB) and secure an acknowledgement receipt of adjusted GPB from the DILG to ensure the compliance of their adjustments to the requirements of the joint memorandum circular on the localization of the Magna Carta of Women; 

(ii) fully integrate the approved GAD Plan and Budget submitted to the DILG in the annual budget and corresponding AIP of the Municipality; and 

(iii) create a GAD Desk to comply with the existing GAD Code.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to instruct the Accounting and Treasury Offices to (i) continue to withhold and remit taxes to the BIR in compliance with existing tax rules and regulations; 

(ii) design effective strategy that will result in the remittance of amount that is reconciled with actual taxes withheld; and 

(iii) exert best effort to trace the source of the unreconciled balance of ₱5,668.43.

